          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-family:Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; font-size: 13px" width="572">
           <tr>
            <td align="left" bgcolor="#e5e5cc" colspan="9" valign="top" width="572">
             <img align="left" alt="" border="0" height="60" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="30"/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="12" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <strong>
              <font color="#FF0000">
               Are your inline effects ever REALLY off?
              </font>
             </strong>
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="2" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <font style="font-size: 18px">
              <strong>
               Build this bypass pedal to turn your stompboxes
              </strong>
             </font>
             <font color="#FF0000" style="font-size: 18px">
              <strong>
               OFF
              </strong>
             </font>
             <font style="font-size: 18px">
              <strong>
               !
              </strong>
             </font>
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="4" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <font style="font-size: 10px">
              <em>
               Erick Coleman, March 3, 2011
              </em>
             </font>
            </td>

           <tr>
            <td align="left" bgcolor="#e5e5cc" colspan="9" valign="top" width="572">
             <img alt="Cartoon: bypass pedal" border="0" height="182" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/ts0134introA.gif" width="151"/>
             <img alt="Cartoon: bypass pedal" border="0" height="182" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/ts0134introB.gif" width="233"/>
             <img alt="Cartoon: bypass pedal" border="0" height="182" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/ts0134introC.jpg" width="187"/>
            </td>

           <tr>
            <td align="left" colspan="4" valign="top" width="208">
             <img alt="Photo: effects pedals" border="0" height="136" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/ts0134pedals.jpg" style="display:block;" width="208"/>
            </td>
            <td align="left" valign="top" width="247">
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <strong>
              <font color="#FF0000">
               Some effects pedals arent true bypass.
              </font>
             </strong>
             Even when the pedal is off, the guitars signal still passes through the circuitry, causing a slight coloration of the tone. This is especially true of vintage style boxes. The more pedals in your effects chain, the more tone is sucked out of your signal to the amp.
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
            </td>
            <td align="left" valign="top" width="8">
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
            </td>
            <td align="left" bgcolor="#cccccc" valign="top" width="1">
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="1"/>
            </td>
            <td align="left" valign="top" width="8">
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
            </td>
            <td align="center" valign="top" width="100">
             <a href="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/archive">
              <img alt="" border="0" height="130" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/sb_archive2.jpg" width="100"/>
             </a>
            </td>
           </tr>
           <tr>
            <td align="left" colspan="5" valign="top" width="455">
             <img align="left" alt="Photo: Dr. Tony Balls" border="0" height="234" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/ts0134mxrtony.jpg" width="83"/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <strong>
              <font color="#FF0000">
               This old MXR Distortion+ pedal is a good example.
              </font>
             </strong>
             Its been a regular part of my live rig for years. Its not a true bypass pedal; I can hear a difference in my tone when its in line but not in use.
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             So I wanted a stomp switch to take this pedal completely out of my signal when not in use. (You probably need this pedal, too.) I turned to my friend Dr. Tony Balls for help. The good Doctors been building me custom pedals for a long time, so I asked him how to wire up a simple, bulletproof, true bypass.
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <strong>
              <font color="#FF0000">
               Heres what the Doctor ordered:
              </font>
             </strong>
             Tony told me how to make this simple wiring project thats fun to build. Following his  instructions, heres how I made myself one:
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
            </td>

            </td>

            </td>
            <td align="left" valign="top" width="8">
            </td>
            <td align="center" valign="top" width="100">
            </td>
           </tr>
           <tr>
            <td align="left" colspan="6" valign="top" width="463">
             <img alt="Photo: measuring, drilling" border="0" height="128" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/ts0134projectbox.jpg" width="455"/>
            </td>
            <td align="left" bgcolor="#cccccc" valign="top" width="1">
            </td>
            <td align="left" valign="top" width="8">
            </td>
            <td align="center" valign="top" width="100">
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <a href="http://www.stewmac.com/Luthier_Tools/Types_of_Tools/Drill_Bits/Brad_Point_Drill_Bit_Sets.html">
              <img alt="" border="0" height="64" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/links/productpix/0339more.jpg" style="display:block;" width="75"/>
             </a>
             <em style="font-size: 9px; color:#666666;">
              Drill Bits, Brad Point
             </em>
            </td>

           <tr>
            <td align="left" colspan="5" valign="top" width="455">
             I started with a small project box from an electronics supply. This box is a Hammond 1590A-BK. I measured and marked locations for five holes (4
             <a href="http://www.stewmac.com/tsarchive/ts0134/Electronics,_pickups/Components:_Jacks/Switchcraft_Output_Jack.html">
              input/output jacks
             </a>
             and 1
             <a href="http://www.stewmac.com/tsarchive/ts0134/Electronics,_pickups/Components:_Switches_and_knobs/3PDT_Stomp_Switch.html">
              stomp switch
             </a>
             ). Using brad point bits, I drilled 3/8" holes for the jacks and a 1/2" hole for the switch.
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <a href="http://www.stewmac.com/Pickups_and_Electronics/Wiring_Kits/Basic_Wiring_Kit.html">
              <img align="left" alt="Photo: soldering" border="0" height="128" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/ts0134soldering.jpg" width="130"/>
             </a>
             I decided not to include an indicator light. Adding a lamp circuit would mean making room for a battery and more wiring. I wanted a super-compact pedal.
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <font color="#FF0000">
              <strong>
               The wiring diagram is super-simple,
              </strong>
             </font>
             and not much wire is needed  the amount included in our
             <a href="http://www.stewmac.com/Pickups_and_Electronics/Wiring_Kits/Basic_Wiring_Kit.html">
              basic wiring package
             </a>
             was more than enough.
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="4" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
            </td>

             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             The photo above shows why it's important to measure before drilling holes: these jacks are
             <em>
              just barely
             </em>
             far enough apart to avoid shorting against each other! Notice too that theres no wire connecting the ground lugs of the jacks. Theres no need to wire them because theyre mounted in an electrically conductive metal case. The case supplies the common ground, keeping things tidy inside the box.
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             If you use a box made of high impact plastic or other non-conductive material you'll need to add that ground wire (indicated in tan on the diagram).
             <br/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>

           <tr>
            <td align="left" colspan="5" valign="top" width="455">
             This diagram adds a light to tell you when the loops in use. Youll need a stereo jack for the input, 3 mono jacks, a battery
             <a href="http://www.stewmac.com/tsarchive/ts0134/Electronics,_pickups/Battery_clips_and_holders/9-Volt_Battery_Mounting_Clip.html">
              mounting clip
             </a>
             and
             <a href="http://www.stewmac.com/tsarchive/ts0134/Electronics,_pickups/Battery_clips_and_holders/9-Volt_Battery_Connector.html">
              connector
             </a>
             , a standard indicator lamp and a 4.7K resistor.
             <br/>
             <img align="right" alt="Photo: Spam can" border="0" height="100" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/ts0134spam.jpg" style="display:block;" width="120"/>
             <img alt="" border="0" height="8" src="http://www.stewmac.com/tradesecrets/newsletter/ts0134/imagekit/8x8hide.gif" style="display:block;" width="8"/>
             <strong>
              To fit the battery along with the switch and four jacks, you'll need
              <font color="#FF0000">
